GLOBAL INSTRUCTION (COMMENT STYLE - BLOCK SEPARATION ONLY)

When adding comments to the code, follow these strict rules:

1. PURPOSE — What comments are allowed
   - ONLY add comments to separate or visually divide relevant sections of the code.
   - DO NOT add explanatory comments describing what the code does.
   - DO NOT narrate logic, behavior, intent, or steps.
   - Comments must serve ONLY as visual separators between logical blocks.

2. COMMENT SHAPE — Mandatory
   The structure must ALWAYS be exactly:

<COMMENT_PREFIX> ────────────────────────────────
<COMMENT_PREFIX> <SECTION TITLE>
<COMMENT_PREFIX> ────────────────────────────────

Where:
- <COMMENT_PREFIX> = `//` for TS/JS/TSX/JSX
- <COMMENT_PREFIX> = `#` for Bash/Shell/Python
- The decorative line MUST be this exact sequence:
  ──────────────────────────────── (no dashes '-', no underscores '_' allowed)
- <SECTION TITLE> must be 1–3 words describing the group of code (e.g., "System Check", "User Routes", "Prisma Types").

3. FORBIDDEN
   - Do NOT add comments explaining logic.
   - Do NOT summarize or describe code behavior.
   - Do NOT generate inline comments.
   - Do NOT use ASCII separators like:
     // ----
     # ------
     # ======
   - Do NOT use block comments /* ... */ unless explicitly requested.

4. PLACEMENT
   - Always place the section header ABOVE the code block it groups.
   - Use section headers ONLY when grouping meaningful or logically connected code.

5. SCOPE
   - Apply this behavior in ALL languages: TypeScript, JS, TSX, Bash, Shell, Python, Go, Rust, etc.
